● Background
Internet usage in Indonesia has seen significant growth in recent years. According to data
from the Indonesian Internet Service Provider Association (APJII), the number of internet
users in Indonesia reached 171.4 million in 2019, representing a penetration rate of around
50 percent. This growth has been driven by a number of factors, including increasing access
to affordable mobile devices and the expansion of broadband infrastructure.[1]
● Problem
One of the key challenges facing internet usage in Indonesia is the digital divide, which
refers to the gap between those who have access to the internet and those who do not. While
urban areas tend to have higher rates of internet penetration, rural areas and lower-income
communities often have limited or no access to the internet. To address this issue, the
Indonesian government has implemented a number of initiatives, including the
development of a national broadband plan and the establishment of community internet
centers.
● Solution
Everyone must have access to the internet in order to improve their work. We are
comparing speed and cost because Indonesia's internet growth is somewhat sluggish. We
can group and forecast the speed and cost of internet service for the following year by
looking at historical data. Additionally, based on the data, we can make some suggestions
to increase internet speed.
We use machine learning techniques to gain the desired output for our project. We aim to
predict the internet speed of Indonesia for the year of 2023, along with clustering different
sets of internet speed in Indonesia as well as finding the correlation between the rate of
internet users and the minimum wage. Therefore, 2 types of machine learning will be used,
which are supervised and unsupervised learning methods. The supervised learning method
would train the data to analyze patterns and predict the future outcome. Meanwhile, the
unsupervised learning method would be used to predict the future data, which is the 2023
internet speed.
We use K-mean method to make a cluster based on the internet speed of Indonesia
provinces and the minimum wage in Indonesia per province, to decide the number of
cluster, we used elbow point that calculate the sum of squared distances for different values
of K,the sum of squared is also known as inertia. The inertia is a measure if the compactness
of the clusters. And also based on internet user in the province and the internet speed of the
province. A decision tree is a type of machine learning algorithm that is used for
classification and regression tasks to classify and identify the increment of the internet
speed.
● Data Gathering
As mentioned earlier, we gathered the data manually because of the intransparency of
internet speed data in Indonesia. We collect the data by scouring the internet to find
separate sources that can give information about the internet speed (download and upload)
especially. Some data was not able to be scraped immediately as it is uploaded to the
internet in an image format, therefore some manual inputs were required.
Internet data that were gathered from Ookla were very limited, as it only provides samples
from 2021 the earliest. As a result, the data gathering process proved to be difficult as there
were not many sources to gather data from, this made the data gathering process take longer
than expected.
For the minimum salary data, it is not too difficult to access it. Each year the government
updates the data on the minimum salary itself. The data itself is open to the public, but each
province is not merged into one big data, which makes us have to gather them one by one.
The data for the percentage of people that use the internet is also quite the same as the
minimum salary data. The data are posted publicly but the challenge here is that some of
the provinces' official websites don't provide the data for the percentage, so we need to
look down for verified third parties data-gathering organizations to collect the missing data.
After we gather the percentage of the people, we need to have the exact number of people
who use the internet. Fortunately, the data for each province's residents are easily accessed.
All of the data that we gathered are from 2020-2022.

Dataset of internet speed ((Upload + Download)/2) from 2020-2021 and 2021-
2022.
The reason we want to make 2 tests and use 2 kinds of testing sample is because
we want to show you the significant level between 2021-2022 and 2020-2021.
Because from our observation of the dataset, we found that there is a huge
increment in the year 2020 in comparison with 2021 to 2022.
○ Null Hypothesis
there is no difference in internet speeds between the two years.
○ Alternative hypothesis
There is a difference in internet speeds between the two years.
○ Calculation 2020-2021
■ Treatment 1
N1: 34
df1 = N - 1 = 34 - 1 = 33
M1: 13.06
SS1: 128.17
s21 = SS1/(N - 1) = 128.17/(34-1) = 3.88
■ Treatment 2
N2: 34
df2 = N - 1 = 34 - 1 = 33
M2: 15.89
SS2: 272.89
s22 = SS2/(N - 1) = 272.89/(34-1) = 8.27
■ T-value calculation
s2p = ((df1/(df1 + df2)) * s21) + ((df2/(df2 + df2)) * s22) = ((33/66) * 3.88) +
((33/66) * 8.27) = 6.08
s2M1 = s2p/N1 = 6.08/34 = 0.18
s2M2 = s2p/N2 = 6.08/34 = 0.18
t = (M1 - M2)/√(s2M1 + s2M2) = -2.83/√0.36 = -4.74
■ Result
The t-value is -4.73662. The p-value is < .00001. The result is significant at
p < .05.
Since p-value is less than 0.05, it would indicate that there is a statistically
significant difference in internet speeds between sample 1 and sample 2.
○ Calculation 2021-2022
■ Treatment 1
N1: 34
df1 = N - 1 = 34 - 1 = 33
M1: 15.89
SS1: 272.89
s21 = SS1/(N - 1) = 272.89/(34-1) = 8.27
■ Treatment 2
N2: 34
df2 = N - 1 = 34 - 1 = 33
M2: 17.32
SS2: 324.22
s22 = SS2/(N - 1) = 324.22/(34-1) = 9.82
■ T-value calculation
s2p = ((df1/(df1 + df2)) * s21) + ((df2/(df2 + df2)) * s22) = ((33/66) * 8.27) +
((33/66) * 9.82) = 9.05
s2M1 = s2p/N1 = 9.05/34 = 0.27
s2M2 = s2p/N2 = 9.05/34 = 0.27
t = (M1 - M2)/√(s2M1 + s2M2) = -1.43/√0.53 = -1.96
■ Result & conclusion of the t test
The t-value is -1.96041. The p-value is .027086. The result is significant at
p < .05.
Since p-value is less than 0.05, it would indicate that there is a statistically
significant difference in internet speeds between sample 1 and sample 2.
The t-value is a measure of the difference between the means of the two
samples being compared, with respect to the spread of the data in the
samples. In this case, the t-value of -1.96041, means that the mean of the
first sample is less than the mean of the second sample, and the difference
is 1.96041 standard deviations.
The p-value is the probability of observing a t-value as extreme or more
extreme than the one calculated, assuming that the null hypothesis (that
there is no difference between the means of the two samples) is true. In this
case, the p-value of .027086, means that there is a 2.7% chance that the
difference in means between the two samples is due to random chance.
In the second case, the t-value is -1.96041 which means that the mean of the
first sample is less than the mean of the second sample, and the difference
is 1.96041 standard deviations. The p-value is .027086, which means that
there is a 2.7% chance that the difference in means between the two samples
is due to random chance. Although the result is significant at p < .05, the
difference between the two samples is relatively small.
In the second case, the t-value is -4.73662, which means that the mean of
the first sample is less than the mean of the second case, and the difference
is 4.73662 standard deviations. The p-value is < .00001, which means that
there is less than 0.01% chance that the difference in means between the
two samples is due to random chance. The result is also significant at p <
.05.
The difference between the second case is much larger than the first case.

○ Sum of Squares Between Groups
SSB = n1 * (mean1 - overall_mean)^2 + n2 * (mean2 - overall_mean)^2 + ... + nk
* (meank - overall_mean)^2
where:
● n1, n2, ..., nk are the number of observations in each group
● mean1, mean2, ..., meank are the means of each group
● overall_mean is the mean of all observations
In this specific example,
● n1=n2=n3 = 34
● mean1 = 13.058529411765
● mean2 = 15.890441176471
● mean3 = 17.320580882353
● overall_mean = 15.423183823529
● Therefore, the SSB is calculated to be 319.9412.
○ Sum of Squares Within Groups
The equation calculates the sum of squares within groups (SSW) for a one-way
ANOVA. It can be written more clearly as:
SSW = (n1-1) * s1^2 + (n2-1) * s2^2 + ... + (nk-1) * sk^2
where:
● n1, n2, ..., nk are the number of observations in each group
● s1, s2, ..., sk are the standard deviations of each group
In this specific example,
● n1=n2=n3 = 34
● (34-1) * s1^2 = (34-1) * 1.9708^2
● (34-1) * s2^2 = (34-1) * 3.4862^2
● (34-1) * sk^2 = 34 * (17.320580882353 − 15.423183823529)^2
Therefore, the SSW is calculated to be 725.2861.
○ Total Sum of Squares
SSB+SSW = 1045.2273
○ Mean Square Between Groups
MSb = SSb/(k-1)
Msb = 319.9412/(3-1)
Msb = 159.9706
○ Mean Square Within Groups
MSw = SSw/(N-k)
Msw = 725.2861/(102-3)
Msw = 7.3261
○ Test Statistic for One Way ANOVA Test\
F = MSb/MSw
F = 159.9706/7.3261
F = 21.8357

○ Null hypothesis
There is no significant difference in the mean internet speed between the 3
treatments. In mathematical terms, it would be stated as:
H0: μ1 = μ2 = μ3
Where:
● H0 is the null hypothesis
● μ1, μ2, and μ3 are the population means of the internet speed for the
3 treatments from year 2020-2022
This null hypothesis assumes that the mean internet speed for each treatment
is equal, and any differences observed in the sample data are due to random
chance.
○ Alternative hypothesis
There is a significant difference in the mean internet speed between the 3
treatments, which can be stated as:
Ha: at least one of the μi is different from the others.
○ Result
Because from the anova test we got F-Stat 21.8357. It will reject the null
hypothesis because the critical value of DF 101 with 3 treatments is
approximated between 3.08 and 3.15.
● Pearson Correlation
R = 1 indicates a perfect positive correlation, meaning the two variables move in the same
direction (i.e. when one variable increases, the other variable also increases)
R = -1 indicates a perfect negative correlation, meaning the two variables move in opposite
directions (i.e. when one variable increases, the other variable decreases)
R = 0 indicates no correlation, meaning there is no relationship between the two variables.
○ 2020-2022
X values = 2020 internet speed
Y values = 2021 internet speed
○ Calculation
● X Values
○ ∑ = 443.99
○ Mean = 13.059
○ ∑(X - Mx)2 = SSx = 128.174
● Y Values
○ ∑ = 540.275
○ Mean = 15.89
○ ∑(Y - My)2 = SSy = 272.891
● X and Y Combined
○ N = 34
○ ∑(X - Mx)(Y - My) = 167.955
● R Calculation
○ r = ∑((X - My)(Y - Mx)) / √((SSx)(SSy))
○ r = 167.955 / √((128.174)(272.891)) = 0.898
● Meta Numerics (cross-check)
r = 0.898
○ Result
A value of R = 0.898 means that there is a strong positive correlation
between the two variables. It suggests that as one variable increases, the
other variable also increases, and the relationship between them is linear.
The coefficient of 0.898 means that there is a very high correlation between
the two variables. The greater the value of R, the stronger the correlation.
○ 2021-2022
X values = 2021 internet speed
Y values = 2022 internet speed
○ Calculation
● X Values
○ ∑ = 540.275
○ Mean = 15.89
○ ∑(X - Mx)2 = SSx = 272.891
● Y Values
○ ∑ = 588.9
○ Mean = 17.321
○ ∑(Y - My)2 = SSy = 324.221
● X and Y Combined
○ N = 34
○ ∑(X - Mx)(Y - My) = 297.451
● R Calculation
○ r = ∑((X - My)(Y - Mx)) / √((SSx)(SSy))
○ r = 297.451 / √((272.891)(324.221)) = 1
● Meta Numerics (cross-check)
r = 1
○ Result
A value of R = 1 means that there is a perfect positive correlation between
the two variables. This implies that as one variable increases, the other
variable also increases, and the relationship between them is linear. The
coefficient of 1 means that there is a perfect correlation between the two
variables. The greater the value of R, the stronger the correlation.
Where
● X: X Values
● Y: Y Values
● Mx: Mean of X Values
● My: Mean of Y Values
● X - Mx & Y - My: Deviation scores
● (X - Mx)2 & (Y - My)2: Deviation Squared
● (X - Mx)(Y - My): Product of Deviation Scores
○ Graph
○ Conclusion
Both results indicate a positive correlation between the two variables, which means
that high values of one variable tend to go with high values of the other variable.
However, the strength of the correlation is different.
A Pearson correlation coefficient of r = 0.898 indicates a strong positive correlation
between the two variables. It suggests that there is a very high linear relationship
between the two variables. The coefficient of 0.898 means that there is a very high
correlation between the two variables.
A Pearson correlation coefficient of r = 1 indicates a perfect positive correlation
between the two variables. It suggests that there is a perfect linear relationship
between the two variables. The coefficient of 1 means that there is a perfect
correlation between the two variables.
In summary, both results suggest that there is a positive correlation between the two
variables, but the second result indicates a stronger correlation than the first one.
● Conclusion
From our testing for our dataset, we got a result that rejects all of our null hypotheses.
Which means from our 3 treatments or the 3 samples on internet speed from 2020 until
2022, there are significant differences between each table. Even though they are highly
significant differences. We also compare the significant level between the years 2020-2021
and 2021-2022, and we found out that the difference of 2020-2021 is much more significant
in comparison with 2021-2022. We assume that is because in 2020 is the start of the
pandemic era in our country Indonesia, that is why internet speed in 2020 gained so much
increment in only one year, while from 2021 to 2022 the increment is not pushed as much
in 2020. To back our assumption up, we also perform pearson correlation and check
correlation between 2020-2021 and 2021-2022, and for a result we got that two of the
treatment have high positive correlation, however our assumption was right, because in
2021-2022 with pearson correlation we got a perfect correlation, which mean it is a stronger
correlation compare to last year sample. So, we assume from the correlation and all of the
tests, in 2023 the significant level will also decrease and internet speed in Indonesia will
be higher. However, there is still a gap between rural and country area internet speed.
